  "nursesNote": "Relaxation techniques lower physiologic arousal and help with anxiety, stress, pain, and insomnia. Deep diaphragmatic breathing uses slow, deep breaths to calm the body. Progressive muscle relaxation (PMR) tenses then releases muscle groups to release tension. Guided imagery has the patient picture a peaceful, calming scene, and mindfulness focuses attention on the present moment. The nurse teaches in a quiet, comfortable setting and has the patient practice regularly so the skill is ready when needed. These skills are best learned when the patient is calm or only mildly anxious, not in the middle of a panic attack. They are safe, nondrug, low-risk options used alongside other care.",
